# Resources

In our daily life, We see various kinds of things like stones, sand, paper, pencil, house, etc. But some of these are usable and some of them are not. These things have been gifted to us by nature. They are essential for our existence on this planet and without them, it is impossible for us to live on this planet. Thus, Resources play a very important role in life sustenance. For example, We can say that oxygen is a resource for all human beings, animals and trees because it is the only life supporting gas. Can you give any other examples of resources that we see around us? Yes, trees are also another example of resources as they provide certain necessary things to us such as foods, fruits, vegetables, woods for making furniture, etc. So anything which is necessary for our existence on this planet is defined as a resource.


Fig 1.0 (Plants)

Even human beings are also considered as a resource because every human being is valuable and it is with the help of the knowledge of the humans that the other resources can be developed.


Fig 2.0 (Human Resources)


∆ Utility and Value

The utility and value of a resource keeps on changing time to time and place to place. For example, The resource water was earlier used by the early humans to irrigate their field, bathing, etc. But now water is a multipurpose resource. Multipurpose resources are defined as the resources which have multiple or many purposes. Water now has many modern uses . It

is now used to run industries, generate electricity (Hydroelectricity), etc. The modern uses of water are now combined with both the ancient uses and the uses of now. So water is obviously a very important resource for all. Wind energy is also another resource because wind can also be used to generate electricity. But unfortunately, China and the USA are generating more wind energy than India. It is because India is not as developed as those two countries.


Fig 3.0 (Water resource)

Fig 4.0 (Wind energy)


∆ Human needs and wants

Human needs and wants are not the same all over the world and are not always constant over the years. It becomes more and more complex as society evolves. In early times, the basic needs of the people were food, cloth and shelter. Although this is our basic need for now as well, we don't focus on those three things, do we? In fact, In advanced societies, more emphasis is laid on utilisation of resources. Let's learn how they are done.


∆ Utilisation of resources

Resources can be utilised when they are processed. For example, We can't directly use silk to make a silk saree,

We have to take care of silkworms, kill them in hot water and then take the thread out from the coccouns etc. So the utilisation of resources depends on the following six factors:-

  • Availability of resources

  • Skill of human beings

  • Availability of capital

  • Availability of water

  • Advancement of technology

  • Availability of transport and communication facilities.

Any resource no matter whatever it is, to make it usable, the above six factors are responsible for it. Let's say that water can be used to generate electricity but water is not present! Then how can we generate electricity without water? According to the first factor, availability of resources is very much important for their utilisation. Say water is there now with us but we don't know how to utilise it, so how can we generate electricity without the skill of human beings? Technology is required to generate electricity from water. If there is no technology to generate electricity by water, then we just can't generate electricity from water.

∆ Developing and Developed nations

A country is given the status of developed or developing on the basis of its economic conditions and technology. A developed country is economically self-suﬃcient and technologically advanced. What can you predict about India? Is it a developed or a developing country? Well, just think for a minute. Is India economically self-sufficient? If India is economically self-sufficient then why are there many economically poor people living in India? And if it is technologically highly advanced, then why are we facing so many Internet issues or any technology issued. So if we think just for a while, then India is given the status of a developing country.


∆ Classification of resources

Resources are classified into many types because it helps us to identify a particular type of resource. Resources are classified on the basis of the following:-

  • Renewability

  • Origin

  • Occurrence

  • Development

    It can be understood easily with the help of a ﬂowchart given on the next page:-

    ∆ Renewable resources

    Renewable resources are also known as inexhaustible resources because they keep on renewing and never get exhausted. Resources which can be renewed either naturally or by human efforts are known as renewable resources. For example, Solar energy, wind energy, water, etc. As solar energy is renewable, it is advised to use solar energy in the homes for various purposes by installing solar panels on the roofs of our homes. Many villages of different states have started this practice of using solar energy.


    Fig 5.0 (Solar panels)


    ∆ Non-Renewable resources

    Non-renewable resources are also known as exhaustible resources because on optimum utilisation of those resources, they might get exhausted!

    Resources which take millions of years to form or renew are known as non-renewable resources. For example, coal, petroleum and other minerals. Some of the non-renewable metallic ores like gold and silver may be used again and again by recycling.


    Fig 6.0 (Petroleum)


    ∆ Biotic resources

    Resources that are available on the biosphere and have life are known as biotic resources. For example, plants, trees, animals, etc. All the biotic resources are renewable as they have the capacity to reproduce and regenerate.

    Fig 7.0 (Forests)

    ∆ Abiotic resources

    All non-living resources are known as abiotic resources. For example, soil, water, etc. All abiotic resources are non-renewable except water which is renewable or inexhaustible.


    Fig 8.0 (Soil resource)

    ∆ Natural resources

    Natural resources are the resources available in the form of plants, trees, etc and are utilised by nature are known as natural resources. Human beings use Natural resources for most of their uses.


    Fig 9.0 (Natural resources)

    ∆ Man-made resources

    Resources made by humans for satisfying their needs are known as man-made resources. For example, roads, buildings, etc. In fact, Man-made resources are made by Natural resources.

    Fig 10.0 (Man-made resources)


    Educated and literate people contribute very much to their society whereas uneducated and illiterate people don't contribute much to their society. Human resources are well developed in Japan because most of their people are well educated and skilled. But In Africa despite being rich in resources, most of the people are illiterate and uneducated.

    Fig 11.0 (Human resources of Japan)

    ∆ Potential resources

    Resources which are there in a country or in a place but they have not been thoroughly surveyed and not have been fully tapped are known as potential resources. They have to be thoroughly surveyed to estimate their quality and quantity. For example, Petroleum can be found in the old sedimentary rocks of Himalayas or Hydroelectricity can be generated by the force of falling water.


    ∆ Actual resources

    Actual resources of a country are those resources which have been thoroughly surveyed and their quantity has been ascertained. The utilisation of actual resources depends on the technology available.

    For example, Saudi Arabia has 25.9% of the world's oil reserves.

    ∆ Sustainable development

    Sustainable development means development that takes place without damaging the environment. It meets the needs of the present without compromising the needs of the future. It is the need of the hour. Thus it is important that we:-

  • Use all the resources judiciously

  • Conserve the varied species

  • Minimise the depletion of natural resources.

The distribution of resources across the globe is highly uneven. Some countries like the USA and the UK make optimum utilisation of resources. Therefore it is important that we should do resource planning as it might lead to the exhaustion of such resources. So, Mankind will have to face dire consequences.


∆ Conservation of resources

Conservation means sustainable and optimum utilisation of resources. We must conserve the resources by following the 5R's, which are Reduce, Reuse, Recycle, Refuse, Rethink. Conservation is very important for now as well as for the future generations.

Fig 12.0 Conservation of Plants


Every Resource is valuable. So, plants are also valuable. Now, let's start conserving all the resources including plants.
